<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1266,1363]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">
Apart from the characters typical for both the 
<taxonomicName box="[660,791,1268,1291]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="taenioceras">
<emphasis box="[660,791,1268,1291]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">taenioceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[844,945,1266,1291]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heinrichi">
<emphasis box="[844,945,1266,1291]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">heinrichi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species groups (see above), the four species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[226,357,1303,1326]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="taenioceras">
<emphasis box="[226,357,1303,1326]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">taenioceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group are characterized by the lack of a buttonlike projection on the last segment of the male antenna (
<figureCitation box="[253,322,1338,1363]" captionStart="FIGURE 1 – 9. 1" captionStartId="3.[151,249,1880,1902]" captionTargetBox="[187,1411,337,1858]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[187,1411,337,1859]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1 – 9. 1: Hoplitis haplophylli, clypeus of female. 2: Hoplitis haplophylli, sterna 3 – 6 of male. 3: Hoplitis haplophylli, terga 4 – 7 of male. 4: Hoplitis haplophylli, antenna of male. 5: Hoplitis taenioceras, antenna of male. 6: Hoplitis heinrichi: tarsus of middle leg. 7: Hoplitis heinrichi: last antennal segment of male. 8: Hoplitis illustris: last antennal segment of male. 9: Hoplitis heinrichi: brood cell in preexisting insect burrow in the ground, which is entirely constructed from chewed leaves; below the cell, a partition of chewed leaves has been built, separating the cell from the lower part of the burrow." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230854/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">
Fig. 
<number box="[306,322,1338,1363]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
